That's all pretty standard.

237
00:12:42,801 --> 00:12:45,743
We went a little step further and we commissioned an author

238
00:12:45,743 --> 00:12:49,404
to write us a custom fairy tale that really helped

239
00:12:49,404 --> 00:12:51,846
kind of explain why the characters had that power.

240
00:12:51,846 --> 00:12:54,527
So the rule book, we kind of sprinkled

241
00:12:54,527 --> 00:12:55,907
these excerpts throughout.

242
00:12:55,907 --> 00:13:00,189
So from this fairy tale, you can see why the 11 and the one,

243
00:13:00,189 --> 00:13:02,270
which is the monarch and the swan, interact.

244
00:13:02,270 --> 00:13:05,872
Just as a little way to help, every little thing you can do

245
00:13:05,872 --> 00:13:07,833
to help a character or a player remember,

246
00:13:07,833 --> 00:13:10,634
what does the 11 do, why is the one related to it,

247
00:13:10,634 --> 00:13:11,455
those kinds of things.

248
00:13:12,121 --> 00:13:14,724
And really, as you're playtesting,

249
00:13:14,724 --> 00:13:17,567
I strongly encourage you always to look at playtesting

250
00:13:17,567 --> 00:13:19,249
as usability testing as well.

251
00:13:19,249 --> 00:13:22,933
Of course, early on, you don't know if people

252
00:13:22,933 --> 00:13:25,095
are gonna enjoy the mechanics that you have,

253
00:13:25,095 --> 00:13:27,898
but as those mechanics start to get refined as...

254
00:13:28,519 --> 00:13:31,001
players are consistently having fun with the game,

255
00:13:31,001 --> 00:13:33,682
you can really start to take a look at the usability,

256
00:13:33,682 --> 00:13:34,843
how players interact.

257
00:13:34,843 --> 00:13:37,585
With Fox in the Forest, we asked players,

258
00:13:37,585 --> 00:13:39,586
after they played, we'd quiz them a little bit.

259
00:13:39,586 --> 00:13:41,587
Hey, what's the power on the three?

260
00:13:41,587 --> 00:13:44,469
Which character lets you change the trumpsuit?

261
00:13:44,469 --> 00:13:45,950
What number is the fox?

262
00:13:45,950 --> 00:13:47,390
And as we play tested that,

263
00:13:47,390 --> 00:13:49,312
especially once we put the character numbers

264
00:13:49,312 --> 00:13:50,132
in the top corner.

265
00:13:50,532 --> 00:13:54,155
that definitely improved. And so we were able to get players by

266
00:13:54,155 --> 00:13:58,257
testing them as well as the game to see where was

267
00:13:58,257 --> 00:14:01,880
it starting to become easy to learn, easy to remember what they're doing.

268
00:14:01,880 --> 00:14:06,703
Now just to give you some context on the work I do as a game producer,

269
00:14:06,703 --> 00:14:10,225
if you're not familiar with the board game

270
00:14:10,225 --> 00:14:14,447
process or how board games today get made, typically what happens is a game

271
00:14:14,447 --> 00:14:18,630
designer will create a prototype and pitch it to a publisher.

272
00:14:18,630 --> 00:14:19,771
It's a bit like an author.

273
00:14:20,551 --> 00:14:27,316
submitting work to a publisher, looking, the author will write a manuscript, here the prototype will be fully playable,

274
00:14:27,316 --> 00:14:33,941
it will have been tested, been found to be fun, it will even have some clean graphic design, probably maybe some clip art,

275
00:14:33,941 --> 00:14:39,945
or some stock photos to help set the atmosphere of the game. But I won't have any of that artwork done yet.

276
00:14:39,945 --> 00:14:43,948
They'll pitch it to a publisher, that will come in, and...

277
00:14:44,388 --> 00:14:49,613
Someone at the publishing company will take on the role of game producer, which is continue

278
00:14:49,613 --> 00:14:52,155
play testing, continue development.

279
00:14:52,155 --> 00:14:56,099
On the board game side, we have a little bit different terminology for designer and development

280
00:14:56,099 --> 00:15:02,064
than you might find in the video game world, because a designer can, a game designer can

281
00:15:02,064 --> 00:15:07,649
make a complete, fun, functioning game without any special programming skills, any of that.

282
00:15:07,649 --> 00:15:10,532
So for development at a publishing house.

283
00:15:11,728 --> 00:15:13,649
a bit like an editor in that book process.

284
00:15:13,649 --> 00:15:15,190
So the author will write the book,

285
00:15:15,190 --> 00:15:17,611
then they'll work with an editor to refine it.

286
00:15:17,611 --> 00:15:20,353
And at that point, a developer is really

287
00:15:20,353 --> 00:15:25,276
helping the designer refine the game, play test it.

288
00:15:25,276 --> 00:15:28,378
And then, of course, you're looking at artwork and layout.

289
00:15:28,378 --> 00:15:31,520
So it'll commission the artist, commission a graphic designer

290
00:15:31,520 --> 00:15:34,241
to kind of handle all that work and get it ready.

291
00:15:34,241 --> 00:15:36,322
And so when the game producer's work is done,

292
00:15:36,322 --> 00:15:37,923
what you have is a product design

293
00:15:37,923 --> 00:15:38,864
ready to go to the printer.

294
00:15:39,224 --> 00:15:43,748
Usually a bunch of PDFs is the output of this process.

295
00:15:43,748 --> 00:15:47,071
At each step of the way, you're continually checking for usability.

296
00:15:47,071 --> 00:15:52,876
One of the biggest things I find in my work is a nice, clean prototype has very good graphic

297
00:15:52,876 --> 00:15:53,657
design.

298
00:15:53,657 --> 00:15:57,580
And when you start to add artwork and make it beautiful, that starts to interfere a little

299
00:15:57,580 --> 00:15:58,601
bit with the usability.

300
00:15:58,601 --> 00:16:01,043
And so there's a lot of work that has to be done.

301
00:16:01,043 --> 00:16:03,145
I've got some examples of that that I'll cover as we go.

302
00:16:04,688 --> 00:16:06,928
To dive in on some of the development, I'll start with

303
00:16:06,928 --> 00:16:08,429
one of our games, World's Fair 1893.

304
00:16:08,429 --> 00:16:12,089
This is the prototype that was pitched to me.

305
00:16:12,089 --> 00:16:15,590
You can see there's some public domain paintings on

306
00:16:15,590 --> 00:16:18,851
there, some tokens with icons from a site called

307
00:16:18,851 --> 00:16:21,632
gameicons.net or the Noun Project.

308
00:16:21,632 --> 00:16:24,432
Those are two popular places to find simple, clean icons.

309
00:16:24,432 --> 00:16:27,113
And this was pitched to me.

310
00:16:27,113 --> 00:16:29,433
I evaluated it, played it, and decided I

311
00:16:29,433 --> 00:16:30,193
wanted to publish it.

312
00:16:31,408 --> 00:16:34,772
One of the mechanisms that we changed in the game was the scoring.

313
00:16:34,772 --> 00:16:39,798
So in the game there are five regions and it's, there's three rounds and you're going

314
00:16:39,798 --> 00:16:41,180
to be trying to get the majority.

315
00:16:41,744 --> 00:16:43,924
in an area, you want to have the most influence

316
00:16:43,924 --> 00:16:44,865
in each of the areas.

317
00:16:44,865 --> 00:16:47,605
And at first, the areas all scored

318
00:16:47,605 --> 00:16:49,285
with slightly different point values.

319
00:16:49,285 --> 00:16:51,506
So here, this one, the one on the left

320
00:16:51,506 --> 00:16:53,786
was five points for first, three points for second.

321
00:16:53,786 --> 00:16:55,887
The other one was four points for first,

322
00:16:55,887 --> 00:16:56,647
two points for second.

323
00:16:56,647 --> 00:16:59,467
And one of the things that, the way that that tracked,

324
00:16:59,467 --> 00:17:02,268
that scoring was tracked, was with

325
00:17:02,268 --> 00:17:04,508
generic scoring tokens, variously denominated.

326
00:17:04,508 --> 00:17:06,148
So there I think were one, three, and five.

327
00:17:06,148 --> 00:17:07,409
So if you scored four points,

328
00:17:07,409 --> 00:17:09,929
you'd take a one and a three point token.

329
00:17:10,604 --> 00:17:16,530
There was a lot of back and forth making change. It was a bit too slow for that scoring round.

330
00:17:16,530 --> 00:17:22,635
So we looked at adding a score track. We thought a game like Ticket to Ride has a scoring track and this is a similar weight.

331
00:17:22,635 --> 00:17:28,320
But an important thing to know with Ticket to Ride is you're not scoring ten different things all at once in the middle of the game.

332
00:17:28,320 --> 00:17:29,001
You're scoring...

333
00:17:29,501 --> 00:17:30,902
Every time you build, you score.

334
00:17:30,902 --> 00:17:32,642
And then at the end, there's a big scoring round.

335
00:17:32,642 --> 00:17:35,243
So as we play tested this,

336
00:17:35,243 --> 00:17:36,604
continued to do usability testing,

337
00:17:36,604 --> 00:17:38,484
we found that in the scoring phases,

338
00:17:38,484 --> 00:17:40,965
people would just start to check out a little bit.

339
00:17:40,965 --> 00:17:42,866
And once one player starts to check out,

340
00:17:42,866 --> 00:17:44,246
and everybody starts to check out,

341
00:17:44,246 --> 00:17:46,767
then it takes longer to do the scoring.

342
00:17:46,767 --> 00:17:48,268
And it makes it seem longer.

343
00:17:48,268 --> 00:17:50,288
So the game was playing about 45 to 60 minutes.

344
00:17:50,288 --> 00:17:51,309
People really enjoyed it,

345
00:17:51,309 --> 00:17:53,670
but you could just tell watching them that.

346
00:17:54,420 --> 00:17:56,622
we needed to keep them more engaged.

347
00:17:56,622 --> 00:17:59,163
And so we looked at, and this was more trouble

348
00:17:59,163 --> 00:18:00,784
than you might think to try to figure out

349
00:18:00,784 --> 00:18:02,785
the best way to track the scoring.

350
00:18:02,785 --> 00:18:04,526
So what we ended up doing was we changed

351
00:18:04,526 --> 00:18:06,507
all of the regions to be worth four and two.

352
00:18:06,507 --> 00:18:09,409
Then what we could do is just have a four point

353
00:18:09,409 --> 00:18:12,250
first place token and a two point second place token.

354
00:18:12,250 --> 00:18:14,211
It's much easier to just pass those out

355
00:18:14,211 --> 00:18:16,713
than it is to count out who's blue,

356
00:18:16,713 --> 00:18:18,854
let me count you four spaces on the scoring track.

357
00:18:19,214 --> 00:18:21,616
Or even handout just varies to, oh, you need a three and a one.

358
00:18:21,616 --> 00:18:22,057
Oh, you've got 10.

359
00:18:22,057 --> 00:18:23,098
Let me make change.

360
00:18:23,098 --> 00:18:26,320
So you can much more easily get through the scoring.

361
00:18:26,320 --> 00:18:29,503
Around the game now plays in about 30 to 40 minutes.

362
00:18:29,503 --> 00:18:33,327
And reviewers always talk about how great the game is for its

363
00:18:33,327 --> 00:18:35,028
decisions versus the time.

364
00:18:35,028 --> 00:18:36,850
And reviewers will always mention that.

365
00:18:36,850 --> 00:18:38,951
They'll be like, man, for a 30 minute game, this has a lot

366
00:18:38,951 --> 00:18:39,552
of decisions.

367
00:18:39,552 --> 00:18:42,314
And we found in play testing that at 45 to 60 minutes, it

368
00:18:42,314 --> 00:18:44,216
just wasn't quite delivering the

369
00:18:44,216 --> 00:18:45,377
satisfaction that we wanted.

370
00:18:47,670 --> 00:18:51,511
Another example of a fun component is from a game called Camel Up.

371
00:18:51,511 --> 00:18:54,831
If you've ever played this game, it's hilarious.

372
00:18:54,831 --> 00:18:57,432
You're watching a camel race.

373
00:18:57,432 --> 00:18:59,352
You're betting on this camel race.

374
00:18:59,352 --> 00:19:03,813
And the way the camels move is there's one die matching each color of the camel, and

375
00:19:03,813 --> 00:19:05,914
they can move one, two, or three spaces each round.

376
00:19:05,914 --> 00:19:08,294
Each camel will move one space.

377
00:19:08,294 --> 00:19:12,955
Now to roll the dice, they have this pretty crazy pyramid contraption.

378
00:19:12,955 --> 00:19:16,316
It comes in the box, has a piece of cardboard, you fold it up, wrap a rubber band around

379
00:19:16,316 --> 00:19:16,356
it.

380
00:19:16,836 --> 00:19:19,057
and it's got this little trigger.

381
00:19:19,057 --> 00:19:21,578
So to roll a die, you flip it face up,

382
00:19:21,578 --> 00:19:23,558
you push in the lever, pull it back,

383
00:19:23,558 --> 00:19:25,899
one die falls out, and then you lift it up

384
00:19:25,899 --> 00:19:29,160
and you reveal, oh, the white camel moves one space.

385
00:19:29,160 --> 00:19:30,441
Now I hear a lot of people all the time say,

386
00:19:30,441 --> 00:19:31,741
well, that's ridiculous, you didn't need

387
00:19:31,741 --> 00:19:34,382
this crazy pyramid, right?

388
00:19:34,382 --> 00:19:37,063
And that could be true, you could just put the dice

389
00:19:37,063 --> 00:19:39,944
in a bag and pull them out, pull one out and then roll it.

390
00:19:39,944 --> 00:19:41,825
But what's interesting there is that

391
00:19:41,825 --> 00:19:42,925
when you're rooting for a camel,

392
00:19:42,925 --> 00:19:44,346
you're like, I really need that blue camel

393
00:19:44,346 --> 00:19:45,946
to move two or three spaces.

394
00:19:46,657 --> 00:19:49,478
If they drew out a white die, you'd be like, oh, I don't care

395
00:19:49,478 --> 00:19:51,219
about the number on the white die.

396
00:19:51,219 --> 00:19:52,559
So you check out.

397
00:19:52,559 --> 00:19:56,621
This way you reveal the color and the number at the same

398
00:19:56,621 --> 00:19:59,482
time, keeps everyone engaged until it's revealed.

399
00:19:59,482 --> 00:20:01,883
There's no partial revealing of information.

400
00:20:01,883 --> 00:20:05,084
Again, silly, nice little touch, but it does, it keeps

401
00:20:05,084 --> 00:20:06,524
the color and the number hidden until

402
00:20:06,524 --> 00:20:07,545
the exact same moment.

403
00:20:08,923 --> 00:20:13,669
One of the things in tabletop that we often do as publishers is re-theme games.

404
00:20:13,669 --> 00:20:15,872
I don't know how common that is in the video game.

405
00:20:15,872 --> 00:20:19,357
My understanding is that by the time you get into designing and

406
00:20:19,357 --> 00:20:21,781
developing, you're pretty much committed to your theme.

407
00:20:21,781 --> 00:20:25,506
But with tabletop games, the mechanics are abstract enough.

408
00:20:26,227 --> 00:20:29,229
There's a lot that we have to abstract away.

409
00:20:29,229 --> 00:20:33,733
You know, you play a card and that counts as building a resource or building a building.

