481
00:24:09,889 --> 00:24:13,774
And you can look across the table and see what colors everybody else has.

482
00:24:13,774 --> 00:24:18,421
We worried very much about when we add artwork, how easy is it going to be to tell?

483
00:24:18,794 --> 00:24:20,435
that they go together.

484
00:24:20,435 --> 00:24:23,416
So we worked with an artist and tried to figure out a way

485
00:24:23,416 --> 00:24:26,277
to make all of the objects look yellow,

486
00:24:26,277 --> 00:24:28,578
even though not with like a mask

487
00:24:28,578 --> 00:24:30,699
or something to make them look washed out.

488
00:24:30,699 --> 00:24:32,459
Before we commissioned all the artwork,

489
00:24:32,459 --> 00:24:35,461
we wanted to see if something like this was possible.

490
00:24:35,461 --> 00:24:39,442
Could we get photos that were sort of yellowish

491
00:24:39,442 --> 00:24:40,783
and see if they would work together?

492
00:24:40,783 --> 00:24:44,464
So what I did was I found a mobile wallpaper pack.

493
00:24:44,464 --> 00:24:45,365
Mobile wallpapers are

494
00:24:45,905 --> 00:24:49,886
more or less the same size as playing cards, at least the same shape.

495
00:24:49,886 --> 00:24:52,007
And so I created a prototype like this.

496
00:24:52,007 --> 00:24:54,187
You can see the flashlight, the stamp, and the lipstick.

497
00:24:54,187 --> 00:24:58,608
They, of course, don't look anything like that, but those cards were all yellowish.

498
00:24:58,608 --> 00:25:02,029
And for the motives, I got cards that all were kind of reddish.

499
00:25:02,029 --> 00:25:02,690
The blue...

500
00:25:03,235 --> 00:25:06,037
got cards that were all kind of bluish.

501
00:25:06,037 --> 00:25:06,817
And then we played this.

502
00:25:06,817 --> 00:25:08,458
Of course, I didn't play this with outside playtesters,

503
00:25:08,458 --> 00:25:09,938
it was only internal team members,

504
00:25:09,938 --> 00:25:11,659
because that's a little jarring

505
00:25:11,659 --> 00:25:14,940
when you have a prank card and it's a mountain landscape.

506
00:25:14,940 --> 00:25:17,261
But we played with this a number of times to just see,

507
00:25:17,261 --> 00:25:20,543
before we commissioned thousands of dollars worth of artwork,

508
00:25:20,543 --> 00:25:22,524
if the photos, which were different,

509
00:25:22,524 --> 00:25:24,345
but were still kind of bluish,

510
00:25:24,345 --> 00:25:25,765
if they would be able to be played

511
00:25:25,765 --> 00:25:27,146
and seen across the table.

512
00:25:27,566 --> 00:25:30,388
So in the end, this is what the artwork looks like.

513
00:25:30,388 --> 00:25:33,049
So you can see the objects are all yellowish,

514
00:25:33,049 --> 00:25:36,211
the crimes are all bluish, the motives are all reddish.

515
00:25:36,211 --> 00:25:37,512
And it's worked really well.

516
00:25:37,512 --> 00:25:40,193
He did a great job making them all look natural.

517
00:25:40,193 --> 00:25:42,574
Kind of the only comment we had is,

518
00:25:42,574 --> 00:25:45,116
why do all the people wear purple clothes in this town?

519
00:25:45,116 --> 00:25:47,577
Because the suspects are purple.

520
00:25:47,577 --> 00:25:50,859
So that's always a challenge for us

521
00:25:50,859 --> 00:25:52,280
in just about every one of our games

522
00:25:52,280 --> 00:25:55,622
is trying to make the art just as playable as the,

523
00:25:56,976 --> 00:26:01,099
as the prototype and sometimes we have to get pretty creative with that.

524
00:26:02,334 --> 00:26:05,415
We're about out of time, so just to wrap up, I want to remind you of the five elements

525
00:26:05,415 --> 00:26:10,577
of usability. Learnability, how easy is it for people to learn for the first time? Memorability,

526
00:26:10,577 --> 00:26:14,778
how easy is it for people to remember once they've already learned it? Efficiency, how

527
00:26:14,778 --> 00:26:20,080
quickly can they perform the tasks once they know them? Accuracy, how likely or unlikely

528
00:26:20,080 --> 00:26:25,242
are they to make mistakes with errors? There's a lot to be said about rule books in there.

529
00:26:25,242 --> 00:26:28,423
I wish if I had another half hour we could talk about rule books and accuracy.

530
00:26:30,230 --> 00:26:35,657
and then satisfaction. How do people enjoy the game? I want to leave you with a few tips

531
00:26:35,657 --> 00:26:40,683
as you're testing. So when you go into a play test, have very specific things that you're

532
00:26:40,683 --> 00:26:45,709
testing. You know, I mentioned we tested these weird photo versions of the Spy Club artwork.

533
00:26:47,217 --> 00:26:51,279
There will be things that come up, of course, that you can't anticipate, and that's also a big part of testing.

534
00:26:51,279 --> 00:26:55,420
So write down, every time a player makes an error, every time they ask a question.

535
00:26:55,420 --> 00:26:57,841
It's really easy when someone says, how much does this cost again?

536
00:26:57,841 --> 00:27:00,202
To just say, oh, three wood, and move on.

537
00:27:00,202 --> 00:27:01,442
But write that down.

538
00:27:01,442 --> 00:27:05,143
And if you start to see the same questions over and over, say, why do people always ask this?

539
00:27:05,143 --> 00:27:08,325
Is there something we can do to make them not ask it?

540
00:27:08,325 --> 00:27:09,185
Is it not intuitive?

541
00:27:09,185 --> 00:27:12,726
Is it not obvious that a city would be three ore and two wheat?

542
00:27:12,726 --> 00:27:14,147
Will a reference card solve it?

543
00:27:14,724 --> 00:27:18,992
Is there something we need to do to make it more thematic, more memorable?

544
00:27:18,992 --> 00:27:22,919
If you're a game designer, I highly recommend you watch people play other games.

545
00:27:22,919 --> 00:27:26,125
When you play Tess, you're going to be watching people play your game a lot.

546
00:27:26,829 --> 00:27:29,350
But if you've never just sat and watched people play other games,

547
00:27:29,350 --> 00:27:31,990
you won't quite know what you're observing.

548
00:27:31,990 --> 00:27:33,290
You know, you ask people, did you like the game?

549
00:27:33,290 --> 00:27:34,111
They say yes.

550
00:27:34,111 --> 00:27:35,771
You could say, well, we're done then.

551
00:27:35,771 --> 00:27:38,852
But if you've watched people play games that they love,

552
00:27:38,852 --> 00:27:41,432
you'll know if they're responding to your game

553
00:27:41,432 --> 00:27:43,092
like they respond to those games.

554
00:27:43,092 --> 00:27:46,553
It can feel a little weird and creepy to watch people play games, of course.

555
00:27:46,553 --> 00:27:48,333
Conventions are a great place to do it.

556
00:27:48,333 --> 00:27:50,014
If somebody's started a game, just walk up and say,

557
00:27:50,014 --> 00:27:51,034
hey, I've been wanting to learn this.

558
00:27:51,034 --> 00:27:53,434
Can I watch you play for a little while and see if I can learn it?

559
00:27:53,434 --> 00:27:54,275
And then that's not creepy.

560
00:27:58,155 --> 00:28:00,697
And also I'd recommend you study interfaces in other games.

561
00:28:00,697 --> 00:28:03,620
So look at the graphic design in other games.

562
00:28:03,620 --> 00:28:06,042
Look at the way they use score tracks, tokens, coins,

563
00:28:06,042 --> 00:28:07,223
all these things.

564
00:28:07,223 --> 00:28:10,005
This one can be really tricky.

565
00:28:10,005 --> 00:28:12,126
As I was preparing for this, I saw an article

566
00:28:12,126 --> 00:28:15,429
that criticized Dominion for putting the costs

567
00:28:15,429 --> 00:28:17,591
in the bottom left instead of the top left

568
00:28:17,591 --> 00:28:19,853
like other games, like Seven Wonders,

569
00:28:19,853 --> 00:28:21,734
or like Magic, which is in the top right.

570
00:28:21,734 --> 00:28:24,797
But of course, those are in very different contexts.

571
00:28:24,797 --> 00:28:27,158
Again, in Dominion, the card is already on the table.

572
00:28:27,438 --> 00:28:30,921
and you can see it, it's not in your hand at this time.

573
00:28:30,921 --> 00:28:33,203
Again, we looked at World's Fair and a score track,

574
00:28:33,203 --> 00:28:35,144
we said, well, other games use a score track,

575
00:28:35,144 --> 00:28:36,385
but again, that was a different context.

576
00:28:36,385 --> 00:28:40,529
So I do recommend that you study all these games,

577
00:28:40,529 --> 00:28:42,290
other interfaces in games, but be careful

578
00:28:42,290 --> 00:28:44,452
that your situation might be a little different

579
00:28:44,452 --> 00:28:46,974
and be very careful to pay attention to those nuances.

580
00:28:48,464 --> 00:28:49,285
That's all I have for now.

581
00:28:49,285 --> 00:28:52,169
We have time for probably one question, if there is one.

582
00:28:52,169 --> 00:28:55,493
I'll be in the overflow room for more questions after this.

583
00:28:55,493 --> 00:28:58,758
So if anybody has one now, or if we want to just wait till

584
00:28:58,758 --> 00:28:59,799
the overflow, that's fine.

